text: Perhaps you could look into how people are socializing. On the one hand there's social media, but are people using the good, old telephone more often now to talk to friends and relatives they'd otherwise meet in person? How does that change human interaction? How do people feel about it? Also, I know a lot of people who see these times as a chance to take some breathing space from social commitments. Will that have a long term effect on the busy-ness of our social life?

text:
And reading through these comments I _still_ have more to say :flushed: -- the perception of press releases is off. I think it's because big companies do them so little companies assume they must be important, but the only reason big companies do them is for public market requirements. Wall Street requires that certain news goes out on the wire. It's dumb.

I haven't seen any evidence that they matter for SEO and even if there is some tiny benefit, I think there are better ways to get there.

I think <@URAV154AV>'s point about getting execs in the news is really interesting and not one that I've considered. I'm not convinced there aren't better ways to get your executives out there (said just a bit about this in the post), but it's a better reason to do a press release than anything else I've seen :slightly_smiling_face:
